          "course_name": "Social-Emotional Development",
          "curriculum_blurb": "",
          "comment": "Fox is a driven, determined, and energetic young boy who relishes and then devours all that second grade has to offer. He is also a passionate presence in 2A, thriving on challenges and problem solving. Fox possesses an intelligence that drives him to understand a plethora of diverse concepts, and he uses his insights to make unique connections among seemingly disparate ideas.  It is a pleasure as teachers to guide Fox as his persona is one of wonder and curiosity.\n\nFox’s intensity can also lead him to become hyper-focused and unable to transition from one activity to the next. For example, a teacher can call his name numerous times to get his attention during a project, but Fox is most often unresponsive and continues working as though he hasn’t heard the teacher. We have had some success giving Fox a warning well ahead of time that he will need to stop his work. Fox seems to need this extra time to mentally disengage. When he is successful, his teachers are sure to give him lots of praise and reinforcement.\n\nFox can also be impulsive and, at times, has not been able to follow through on a teacher’s direction. Rather, he continues on his course of action even if it is the opposite of what was requested from him. When this happens, we ask Fox to take some time in a separate area of the classroom to discuss with his teachers how to better approach a similar situation the next time.",
