          "course_name": "Social-Emotional Development",
          "curriculum_blurb": "",
          "comment": "Anna is a perceptive, highly observant, and creative young girl who uses her keen sense of humor to delight her peers. Anna is new to Fieldston Lower and at the beginning of the year expressed that she didn’t have any friends in 2A. Fast forward to January, and we now see Anna sometimes laughing and drawing with friends such as Gigi and Abigail. At times, Anna still says that she doesn’t have any “close” friends but, given time, the friendships she is now building have the opportunity to grow into stronger relationships. \n\nAnna continues to have difficulty receiving directions from a teacher.  While we saw nice progress in December and early January, Anna’s challenges have since resurfaced. For example, a request to return to her seat or to settle down often engenders a defensive response and she argues with the teacher the merits of the request. Anna also has difficulty managing situations she finds frustrating. When this happens, Anna struggles to regulate her strong emotions and she can act out by slamming her locker door, throwing books on the floor, or yelling at peers and adults.\n\nOverall, our goal for Anna is for her to come to trust her teachers more and accept that they truly care for her and hold her in high regard. Recently, she revealed a gracious maturity that reflects her true sensitivity. When a teacher had to leave for a doctor’s appointment, she quietly approached her saying, “I really hope your doctor visit goes well. I’ll be thinking about you.”",
