          "course_name": "Approach to Learning",
          "curriculum_blurb": "",
          "comment": "Anna is anxious to do well and holds herself to high standards. Most often this results in exceptional work, particularly in writing and drawing. But, at times, Anna can become frustrated with herself and needs to take a break from the work in order to get some distance and perspective on it. For example, once when painting a picture for her Time of Day book, she became very frustrated that what she put on paper did not match the vision she had in her head. A teacher asked her if she would like to try again another day and she was then able to very gradually recenter herself.\n\nWe also support Anna with her attention throughout the day as she can become both internally and externally distracted. At times this causes her to miss instruction, and she benefits from a teacher privately repeating the directions to her. Anna can also move very slowly in the classroom environment, as though her mind is elsewhere. We support her by giving her extra time for tasks. For example, when it’s time to gather her belongings at dismissal, she benefits from being asked to do so before others so she can be packed up and ready to go with her classmates.",
